{{Infobox royalty | type = monarch | name = Toghrul III | more = | image = | caption = | succession = Last [[List of sultans of the Seljuq Empire|Sultan]] of the [[Great Seljuq Empire]] | reign = 1176-1194 | coronation = | predecessor = [[Arslan Shah]] | successor = Office abolished | full name = | house = | spouse= | father = [[Arslan Shah]] | mother = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = March 19, 1194 | death_place = killed near [[Rey, Iran|Rey]] | place of burial = | religion = }} '''Toghrul III''' ({{lang-fa|طغرل سوم}}) (died 1194) was the last sultan of the [[Great Seljuq Empire]].
The son of sultan [[Arslan Shah]], he succeeded him in 1175 or 1176. In 1190 he tried to free himself from the tutelage of the Atabeg of Azerbaijan, [[Qizil Arslan]], but he was overthrown and imprisoned by the latter, who proclaimed himself sultan.<ref>Grousset, Rene, ''The Empire of the Steppes'', (Rutgers University Press, 1991), 158.</ref> The usurper was assassinated the following year and Toghrul regained his throne. During his brief reign, Toghrul would become quite proficient in Persian poetry.<ref>A.C.S. Peacock, ''The Great Seljuk Empire'', (Edinburgh University Press, 2015), 185.</ref>
On 19 March 1194, he was defeated and killed near [[Rey, Iran|Rey]]<ref>Grousset, 167.</ref> in the war that he had waged against the Shah of Khwarezm, [[Ala ad-Din Tekish]]. Toghrul's head was sent to the Caliph [[An-Nasir (Abbasid Caliph)|Al-Nasir]] who displayed it in front of his palace in Baghdad. The Great Seljuq Empire disappeared with Toghrul's death.
